  "prompt": "What is the meaning of f(2) in calculus?",
  "response": "In calculus, \\( f(2) \\) typically represents the value of a function \\( f \\) evaluated at the point \\( x = 2 \\). \n\nTo elaborate:\n\n- If \\( f(x) \\) is a function defined on a certain domain, then \\( f(2) \\) gives you the specific output of that function when the input is 2.\n- This can be applied in various contexts, such as determining the height of a curve at a certain point, evaluating limits, or finding values related to optimization problems.\n\nFor example, if \\( f(x) = x^2 + 3 \\), then \\( f(2) = 2^2 + 3 = 4 + 3 = 7 \\).\n\nIn summary, \\( f(2) \\) is a straightforward way to denote the output of a function when the input is 2.",
